<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-328-351  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 328 351.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Jan 30 1989 v10 n5 p13(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Chinese pact for satellite launch marks aggressive entry intofield. (Asiasat)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Enrlich, Paul Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Chinese are trying to get a larger share of the satellitetelecommunications market with their low-cost satellite launchindustry.andP;  They face stiff competition from private US firms whichhave also moved into the market since the Challenger disaster.andO;China said that 30 foreign companies have requested assistance inlaunching or recovering satellites.andP;  To take advantage of theserequests, China closed a deal to launch its first US-madesatellite with the Asia Satellite Telecommunications Co (Asiasat).andO;The $30 million contract was signed by the state-owned China GreatWall Industrial Corp. The launch date is set for April 1990.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Asia Satellite Telecommunications Co. (contracts).andO;Topic:     ChinaSatellite CommunicationsMarketing StrategyForeign Competition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>